iRegistration Procedure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen I wrote my previous guide in 2017,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1Joining DN42 Experimental Network	/en/article/modify-website/join-dn42-experimental-network.lantian	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
the user information as well as ASN and IP are all managed from a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isystem called
Monotone. But in the year of 2018, DN42 gave up on		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMonotone and switched to Git.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWARNING:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe registration procedure to DN42 is long and complicated since
the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprocedure to register ASN and IP in the real Internet is similar, and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDN42's
goal is being a replicate to the real Internet.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iATTENTION:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The procedure here may become outdated as DN42 updates its		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iregistration
procedures. Please refer to DN42's official guides first,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand use my guide
only as reference.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hDN42 Registration Procedure on Official Wiki	URL:https://dn42.dev/howto/Getting-Started	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hDN42 Git Guide (Creating Pull Request) on Official Wiki	URL:https://git.dn42.dev/dn42/registry/src/branch/master/README.md	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIn addition, since a bunch of UNIX tools (such as Git, GnuPG) are		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irequired in
the procedure:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- It's recommended to use Linux or macOS for the whole procedure.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you use Windows, you may try		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hWindows Subsystem for Linux	URL:https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/install-win10	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHere are the steps:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- First, go to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://git.dn42.dev	URL:https://git.dn42.dev	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand register an
account. This is the GitHub for DN42, and the account		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinformation is stored
in one of the git repos.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Visit		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hdn42/registry	URL:https://git.dn42.dev/dn42/registry	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, the account
information repo, and click Fork on the top right. This		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwill create a copy of
the repo into your own account.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Previously you can directly create a branch in the repository, but		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inow you
need to fork the repo, just like what you do on GitHub and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isimilar sites.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Now the page should automatically switch to the copy in your own		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iaccount. Git
clone it to your local machine.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Now, you need to create a series of files in the cloned repo,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iincluding:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Create a file `[NICKNAME]-MNT` under `data/mntner` directory. This		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile is
your account that authorizes your further operations. For		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iexample, this is
my `mntner` file (available under		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`data/mntner/LANTIAN-MNT`):		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The items in the file are:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `mntner`: `maintainer`, the name for your account. Same as the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile
name.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `admin-c`: `admin contact`, points to a later created `person`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile.
Usually `[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `tech-c`: `tech contact`, points to a later created `person`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile.
Usually `[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `mnt-by`: `maintain by`, points to this account itself.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iUsually
`[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `source`: has a fixed value of `DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `auth`: your authentication info. Usually, two types of data		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iare
accepted: GPG public key and SSH public key.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- You		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMUST		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iadd at least one out of GPG pubkey and SSH pubkey.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you plan to add a GPG pubkey, you need to create one		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifirst
(assuming you don't have one). You may follow		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hthis guide by GitHub	URL:https://docs.github.com/en/free-pro-team@latest/github/authenticating-to-github/generating-a-new-gpg-key	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i.
You will also need the pubkey when submitting your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iregistration
request.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- You also need to upload your GPG pubkey to a public server,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iaka
Keyserver, for other people to obtain.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Run this command:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `gpg --keyserver hkp://keyserver.ubuntu.com --send-key [GPG Key ID]`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then fill the key ID to `auth` item, with the format		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iof
`pgp-fingerprint [GPG Key ID]`, similar to my example above.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you plan to add an SSH pubkey, you need to create one		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifirst
(assuming you don't have one).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Running `ssh-keygen -t ed25519` is usually enough for Mac and
Linux,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibut if you have a rather old version of SSH, which doesn't
support		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iED25519 crypto, you may run `ssh-keygen -t rsa` instead to
use RSA		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icrypto.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- For Windows, you can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hdownload PuTTY	URL:https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/latest.html	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand use its `puttygen` utility.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- After generation, add your pubkey (usually stored at `~/.ssh`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand
named `id_ed25519.pub` or `id_rsa.pub` on Mac and Linux;		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idisplayed
straight on `puttygen` window after generation) to `auth`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iitem,
with format `ssh-ed25519 [SSH Pubkey]` or `ssh-rsa [SSH		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPubkey]`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In addition, some services on DN42 verify your identity with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyour
SSH pubkey here.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Read DN42's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hRegistry Authentication Wiki Page	URL:https://dn42.dev/howto/Registry-Authentication	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifor more information.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `remarks`: comments, fill with whatever content you like. Or you		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imay
simply remove them.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iATTENTION:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-  There is a long sequence of spaces between the name and
values. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilength of this space sequence		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icannot be changed to
whatever you like, and cannot be replaced with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTAB		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i. The length of the
name, the colon, and the spaces		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMUST be exactly 20 characters		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Create `[NICKNAME]-DN42` under `data/person`. This stands for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyour
personal information, but what's actually needed is simply a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imailbox.
Here's my `person` file, for example		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(`data/person/LANTIAN-DN42`):		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The items in the file are:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `person`: your nickname.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `e-mail`: your e-mail address.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `contact`: optional, your contact information other than e-mail,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ie.g.
IRC or Telegram.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `nic-hdl`: `NIC handle`, points to the file itself. It is the same		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ias
file name, `[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `mnt-by`: `maintain by`, points to the `mntner` file you		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipreviously
created, `[NICKNAME]-MNT`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `source`: has a fixed value of `DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Next, you need to choose for yourself an Autonomous System Number or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iASN.
On the real/global Internet, the ASN range 4200000000 -		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i4294967294 is
reserved for private use, and DN42 occupies one small		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iblock in it,
424242		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i0000		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- 424242		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i3999		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Note that the range contains 4000 ASNs
rather than 10000! The other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i6000 ASNs aren't open to registration yet.)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPick yourself an ASN in the range that you like and is not occupied,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand
create a file for it under `data/aut-num`. For example, I'm		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irunning
AS4242422547, so I have the file `data/aut-num/AS4242422547`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The items in the file are:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `aut-num`: Your ASN.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `as-name`: Name for the AS, usually only visible in some		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork
structure graphs of DN42. The recommended value is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`[NICKNAME]-AS`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `descr`: Description for the AS, usually only visible in some		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork
structure graphs of DN42. Fill with whatever you like.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `admin-c`: `admin contact`, points to your `person`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile,
`[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `tech-c`: `tech contact`, points to your `person`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile,
`[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `mnt-by`: `maintain by`, points to your `mntner`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifile,
`[NICKNAME]-MNT`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `source`: has a fixed value of `DN42`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you have an ASN on the real Internet:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iYou may choose to use your real, global ASN in DN42.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-  Simply use
your own ASN in this step.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you do this, you may run into a bit of trouble when peering		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwith
others：		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- When establishing a VPN connection, many people in DN42 use the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilast
5 digits of your ASN as the port number. In this case, your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipublic
ASN may collide with an internal ASN in DN42.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If this happens, you need to talk to the other side, so you		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ican
connect to another port.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- And your identity may need to be verified, such as checking if		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe
mailbox match what's on the WHOIS information of your global ASN,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ietc.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- I never experienced this sequence, and the verification procedure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis
my guess. Perhaps a more complicated procedure is required.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Generally, I suggest that you		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
