iFinding a Peer Node		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSince DN42 is a decentralized network, there is no official server to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconnect
to. You need to contact other users registered in DN42 just		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilike you, create a
VPN tunnel connection and BGP session, to establish		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipeering.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHere are some recommended places to find other users:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Use		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hDN42 PingFinder	URL:https://dn42.us/peers	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i. Submit your IP address, and
server nodes of other users registered		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ion PingFinder will test their latency
to you. These node entries		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusually have e-mail addresses or links to their
description pages for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itheir DN42 AS. You may contact them with this
information.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Go to DN42's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hIRC channel	URL:https://wiki.dn42.us/services/IRC	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Go to this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hunofficial Telegram group	URL:https://t.me/Dn42Chat	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDirectly go to Burble. Burble is a really active user in DN42 who has		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imany
nodes around the world. Visit		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhis peering info page	URL:https://dn42.burble.com/peering	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito see his server
information and contacts.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- To reduce network centrality and avoid single point failure, Burble		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inow
only accepts users with at least 2 already established peers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Directly go to me. Click		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1here	/en/page/dn42/index.html	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ior the DN42 item on
the top navbar to see my information and contacts.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iYou may peer with many people/nodes simultaneously. It increases the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istability
of your network and prevents loss of connection when a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isingle node fails.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFind a few nodes close to your server with low latency, and proceed		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idownwards.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iVery Important System Configuration		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- First,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMAKE SURE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithat you enabled Linux's packet forwarding, or
`ip_forwarding`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- There is no absolute "client" in DN42. Everyone's server is a router		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifor
others and needs to forward packets. The steps are:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- By the way, if you configured a firewall like `iptables`, check		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe
configuration and make sure they don't block packet forwarding.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMAKE SURE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito disable Linux `rp_filter`'s strict mode:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `rp_filter` is a network security mechanism of the Linux kernel. It		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ichecks
the packet's source address and the source network interface:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If set to 0 (disabled), allow all packets.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Some packets that cannot be replied to correctly (no entries in		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe
routing table) will be processed by userspace applications,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipossibly
consuming extra resources.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- But the overhead should be tiny, so setting to 0 is no issue here.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If set to 1 (strict), if the packet doesn't come from the "best"		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork
interface (or in other words, your machine will reply to the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipacket on a
different network interface), the packet will be		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idropped		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Having different network interfaces for source and reply is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivery
common		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin DN42, so		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMAKE SURE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou don't set `rp_filter` to 1!		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If set to 2 (relaxed),		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iin theory		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, Linux will only drop packets that
don't have a source address in the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irouting table, which means it doesn't
know how to properly reply to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithem.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- However, theory is just theory. In newer versions (5.0+) of the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ikernel,
still, a lot of normal packets with correct source addresses		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iare
dropped. Therefore, don't use this mode, please stick to 0		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinstead.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMAKE SURE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito turn off any tool that helps you configure `iptables`
easily, such		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ias UFW.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- These easy tools may use some assumptions that are suitable for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipersonal
users but are not suitable for DN42, such as using conntrack.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Conntrack filters packets from links it hasn't seen before,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieffectively
doing strict `rp_filter`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- I personally recommend you to configure iptable manually.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iChoose Tunnel Software		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAlmost every peering in DN42 is established on tunneling software (or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iVPN)
since:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- DN42 nodes are spread across the world, and tunneling provides		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibasic
encryption and protection;		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- DN42 uses private addresses that will be dropped by firewalls on the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iInternet.
What's worse, your ISP may think you are doing "IP Spoofing"		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich is a
violation of ToS and cause catastrophic consequences.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBut there are exceptions:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Two nodes connected to the same internal network may be connected		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idirectly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Examples are some NAT VPSes, or Alibaba Cloud servers with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iClassic
Networking.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHere is my recommendation for tunneling software:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you're using a Linux VPS or dedicated server, and you're not		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusing OpenVZ
or LXC, use WireGuard.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Extremely easy to configure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Little resource consumption		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Good security		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cons:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Lack of features, only allow point-to-point connections		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Needs extra kernel modules		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Layer 3 only and doesn't support bridging		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you're using OpenVZ or LXC, `wireguard-go` is not suggested. It's		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inot
updated as frequently, and it's reported by other users to have		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istability
issues.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Installation, on Debian 10 (Buster) as an example:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- First, add Debian Backports repo:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Edit `/etc/apt/sources.list`, add:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then, use DKMS to install WireGuard kernel modules and management		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itools:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `sudo apt update`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- `sudo apt install wireguard-tools wireguard-dkms`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you're using OpenVZ or LXC VPS, use OpenVPN.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Extremely wide usage		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Tons of tutorials		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- No need for any extra kernel module		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Choose between Layer 2 and Layer 2		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cons:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Being a bit complicated to configure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Less secure than WireGuard		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Installation `sudo apt install openvpn supervisor`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Here, Supervisor is for managing processes. You may use others		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilike
`systemd`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you're using a hardware router from Cisco, Mikrotik, etc., you're		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusually
restricted to GRE/IPSec:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Wide use on hardware routers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
