iBuilding Internal Network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you have multiple servers joining DN42, you need to configure your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinternal
network first. Your network needs to satisfy the following		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irequirements to work
normally:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Proper communication (or pingable) between any two servers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Routers outside your AS are only responsible for sending the packet		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito your
own AS, and the packet may enter from any node. Your own node		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ineeds to
forward the packet to the correct node.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- You may use these schemes:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- A full-mesh VPN with Tinc, ZeroTier One, etc., so any two servers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ican
talk directly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-  point-to-point tunnels with OpenVPN, WireGuard,
etc., so any two		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iservers can talk directly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Relatively Dangerous)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-  Use OpenVPN, WireGuard, etc., to create less
than		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itunnels, but make sure there is a path between
any two servers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(intermediate nodes allowed). Then use Babel, OSPF, RIP,
etc., to find		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe path in your own network.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In this scheme, it's easy to make mistakes and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icause catastrophic
failures		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Some real examples are available at		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1How to Kill the DN42 Network	/en/article/modify-website/how-to-kill-the-dn42-network.lantian/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Routing protocols, including Babel, OSPF, RIP, etc., can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iautomatically
detect the topology of your whole network and configure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe routes.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- But Babel, OSPF, RIP are only supposed to handle your internal		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irouting,
and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ishouldn't be used to forward routes received externally from BGP!		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- When BGP routing information is forwarded by Babel, OSPF,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iRIP,
information such as source, route length, and BGP communities are		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iall
lost.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Therefore, your other nodes will think that the route		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icomes from your
own network		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand broadcast the route to others with your AS as the
source.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In short: you will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihijack the whole DN42		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Babel, OSPF, RIP should be strictly restricted to your own IP range.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iExternal routing must be handled by BGP		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you have questions, seek help at		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hthe unofficial Telegram group	URL:https://t.me/Dn42Chat	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- BGP configuration must satisfy one of:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- One BGP session between each of your two servers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- BGP has a feature that, within one AS, a BGP node will only		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibroadcast
routes that it		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ireceived externally		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwon't forward		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iroutes it
received from other internal nodes in the AS. It is to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprevent any
occurrence of route loops. Therefore, each server needs to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iestablish BGP
sessions with all other servers, so it can obtain a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icomplete routing
table.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you have a lot of servers, you will have fun configuring each		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iserver
by hand. You may consider writing a script or using any plan		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibelow.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Configure one server as a `BGP Route Reflector` and establish BGP		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isessions
with all other servers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Route Reflector will manage and broadcast all routing information		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwithin
the AS.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Compared to the last scheme, you will need to do substantially		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iless
configuration, but if the Route Reflector is down, your whole		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork is
dead.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Note that I haven't tried this configuration and cannot provide		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iany
technical help.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you have questions, seek help at		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hthe unofficial Telegram group	URL:https://t.me/Dn42Chat	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, where some users
use this scheme.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Configure a different private ASN at each node, and configure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBGP
Confederation.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- ASN should be in the private ASN range 4200000000 - 4294967294, but		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inot
4242420000 - 4242429999 since it may overlap with other DN42		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- With Confederation, multiple servers team together and appear as one		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAS
when observed externally.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
