i"1xRTT Peering": Faster Peering		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMost users in DN42 are in the United States or Europe. When I contact		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithem from
China, due to the timezone differences, one communication		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icycle can be quite
lengthy. So we should configure our side as		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icompletely as possible based on the
public information of the other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iside. This makes debugging easier for others and
reduces the time		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconsumption in repeated communications.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI have a list on my		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1DN42 Page	/en/page/dn42/index.html	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i, including the
information I'll need when setting up the tunnel and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBGP session and the steps
you should take.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNote that I don't have any special configuration/requirements, and the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilist is a
general requirement for almost any DN42 user. Therefore I		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isuggest that you
follow the list and provide complete information.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHere is a copy of the list for reference:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTunnel Setup: WireGuard		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDN42 Wiki has a WireGuard configuration guide available. I made		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iminor
modifications to it so that it's clearer.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, run `wg genkey | tee privatekey | wg pubkey > publickey` to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
igenerate your
public/private key pair. This is the only authentication		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinfo in a WireGuard
tunnel, so don't leak the private key.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen create a configuration file `[PEER_NAME].conf`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThen run `wg-quick up [PEER_NAME].conf` to set up the tunnel.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTunnel Setup: OpenVPN		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDN42 Wiki also provided an OpenVPN configuration template. I made		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iminor
modifications to it so that it's clearer.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLimit Traffic on DN42 Interfaces		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe tunnel established during a DN42 peering usually allows traffic to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iany IP
(unless you set AllowedIPs for WireGuard), and this creates a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irisk: your peer
can inject packets destined for public IPs to your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itunnel, and your node will
forward them to the public Internet, under		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyour name. If your peer is exploiting
this for a network attack, you		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwill be in great trouble.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, it's recommended that you set up iptables rules to block		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iforwarding
from your peers to the Internet.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> Note: you don't need this if you only use WireGuard. WireGuard		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ialready has IP
limitations built-in.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe following rules will restrict traffic to DN42 IP ranges on all		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinterfaces
with name starting with `dn42-`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
